to other epic traditions—in particular the Iliad—and interaction between the poem and its performance context in Athenian civic ritual. This detailed structural analysis, with its insights into the circumstances and meaning of the Odyssey's composition, will lead to a new understanding of the Homeric epics and the tradition they evoked.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEpic poetry, GreekxHistory and criticism. 0aEpic poetry, GreekxReligious aspects. 0aMythology, Greek, in literature. 0aOdysseus (Greek mythology) in literature. 4aAncient History & Classical Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aNagy, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172350640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501723506423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501723506/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles